There is a number of '''deities and fairies of fate in Slavic mythology''', which control person's destiny or foretell it, often at childbirth. A comprehensive summary may be found in [[Jan Máchal]]'s contribution to Vol. 3 of ''[[The Mythology of All Races]]'' (1918).<ref name=machal>''[[The Mythology of All Races]]'' (1918), Vol. III, Section "Slavic", Part I: The Genii, [https://books.google.com/books?id=-pYYAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA217 Chapter IV: Genii of Fate, pp. 249-252]</ref>
*Ancient Russian deities (written tradition): Rozhanicy (pl.)<ref name=machal/> * Croatians and Slovenians: Rodjenice(pl.),<ref name=machal/> Rojenice(pl.)<ref name=machal/>. They were also called Sudice(pl.), Sudjenice(pl.), Sujenice(pl.) (Croatian), Sojenice(pl.), Sujenice(pl.), Rojenice(pl.) (Slovenian), Sudzenici(pl.) (Bulgarian) or Sudičky(pl.) (Bohemian, i.e., Czech and Slovak)<ref name=machal/> *Serbian: 'Sudice(pl.), Suđaje(pl.) *Bulgarian: Nerechnitse(pl.), Narucnici(pl.) (''narok''= destiny, "neracha"= foretells<ref group=nb>There is no infinitive form of verbs in Bulgarian, i.e., no direct counterpart for "to foretell"</ref>), or Orisnici(pl.), Urisnici(pl.), Uresici(pl.), from the Greek όρίζοντες, ("orizontes": "establishing", "determining")<ref name=machal/> *Russian personifications of the Fate: good fate: {{ill|Dola (mythology)|ru|Доля (мифология)}}, evil fate: Nedolya, [[Likho]] <ref name=machal/> *Serbian: Sreca, counterpart of Dolya, however it may be both good and evil<ref name=machal/> *Polish: Rodzanice(pl.), Narecznice(pl.), Sudiczki(pl.)
