{{Infobox religious group |group = Sad Vaishnavism |image = Udupi Sri Krishna Matha Temple.jpg |caption = '''The Entrance to [[Udupi Sri Krishna Matha|Sri Krishna Matha]] at Udupi''' | scriptures = [[Vedas]], [[Upanishads]], [[Bhagavat Gita]], [[Brahma Sutra]], [[List of works by Madhvacharya|Sarvamula Granthas]] |regions = [[Karnataka]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Tamil nadu]], [[Andhra Pradesh]] | religions = [[Vaishnavism]] (Hinduism) |languages = [[Sanskrit]], [[Kannada]] }} {{Vaishnavism}}
The '''Madhva tradition''' (also referred as '''Madhva Sampradaya''', or '''Sad Vaishnavism''') is a denomination within the [[Vaishnavism]] tradition of [[Hinduism]], founded by the thirteenth century philosopher [[Madhvacharya]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Alternative Krishnas: Regional and Vernacular Variations on a Hindu Deity|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=K0XqbG0LKBUC|publisher=SUNY Press|author=Guy L. Beck|year=2012|page=74}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Rajasthan Through the Ages: Art, architecture and memoirs|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=vZrpAAAAMAAJ|page=333|publisher=Deep & Deep Publications|author=Suresh K. Sharma, Usha Sharma|year=1999}}</ref> It is a movement in [[Hinduism]] that developed during its classical period around the beginning of the Common Era. Philosophically, Madhva tradition is aligned with [[Dvaita Vedanta]], and regards [[Madhvacharya]] as its founder or reformer.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Oriental Philosophy and Religion: A Continuing Series--, Volume 1|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Uec1E8DpiH8C|author1=Nagendra Kr Singh|author2=A. P. Mishra|publisher=Global Vision Pub House|year=2005|page=99}}</ref>
According to Madhva tradition, the creator is superior to the creation, and hence [[moksha]] comes only from the grace of [[Vishnu]], but not from effort.<ref>{{cite book|title=Krishna in History, Thought, and Culture: An Encyclopedia of the Hindu Lord of Many Names: An Encyclopedia of the Hindu Lord of Many Names|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=4fw2DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA165|author=Lavanya Vemsani|publisher=ABC-CLIO|accessdate=13 June 2016|page=165}}</ref>
==Etymology== The term ''Madhva'' is derived from the name of the tradition's founder, Madhvacharya. The term ''sampradaya'' refers to a Hindu religious tradition. The term ''Sad Vaishnavism'' is derived from ''sad'', meaning "true", and the Hindu deity [[Vishnu]], whose worshipers are known as Vaishnavism; this name of the tradition may thus be translated as "true Vaishnavism"<ref>{{cite book|title=Grace in Christianity and Hinduism|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pujRGufjKBAC|publisher=James Clarke & Co|page=179|author=Sabapathy Kulandran|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Saints of India|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=QoQaBgAAQBAJ|publisher=Jagadguru Kripaluji Yog|year=2014|page=contents}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Stephan Schuhmacher |title=The Encyclopedia of Eastern Philosophy and Religion: Buddhism, Hinduism, Taoism, Zen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vpP8770qVakC |date=1994 |publisher=Shambhala |isbn=978-0-87773-980-7 |page=397 }}</ref> The followers of ''Sad Vaishnavism'' are known as ''Sad Vaishnavas''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Famous Indian sages: their immortal messages|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dKnXAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Sagar Publications|page=356|year=1982|author=Vivek Ranjan Bhattacharya}}</ref>
==Philosophy and theology== According to Madhvism, the Divine and the soul are completely distinct from each other.<ref>{{cite book|title=Viṣṇu, the Ever Free: A Study of the Mādhva Concept of God|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=hITXAAAAMAAJ|page=227|publisher=Dialogue Series|author=Ignatius Puthiadam|year=1985}}</ref> Madhva Sampradaya worships Vishnu as the highest Hindu deity and regards [[Madhva]], whom they consider to be an incarnation of Vishnu's son, [[Vayu]], as an incarnate saviour.<ref>{{cite book|title= Encyclopedia Americana: M to Mexico City|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=U_gWAQAAMAAJ|page=59|publisher=Scholastic Library Publishing|year=2006}}</ref> Madhvism regards Vayu as [[Vishnu]]'s agent in this world, and [[Hanuman]], [[Bhima]], and [[Madhvacharya]] to be his three incarnations; for this reason, the roles of Hanuman in the [[Ramayana]] and Bhima in the [[Mahabharata]] are emphasised, and Madhvacharya is particularly held in high esteem.<ref>{{cite book|title=Prāci-jyotī: Digest of Indological Studies, Volume 13|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=28A5AQAAIAAJ|page=245|publisher=Kurukshetra University|year=1977}}</ref> Vayu is prominently shown by Madhva in countless texts.<ref>{{cite book|title=Madhva's Philosophy of the Viṣṇu Faith|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=GITXAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Dvaita Vedanta Studies and Research Founda|author=Helmuth von Glasenapp|year=1992|page=154}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Indian Culture: Journal of the Indian Research Institute, Volume 3, Issues 3-4|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=8mBDAAAAYAAJ|year=1984|publisher=I.B. Corporation|page=505}}</ref>
Madhvacharya, was a staunch Vaishnava who pushed strongly the belief that Vishnu was the highest of Hindu deities, and refused to accept any claims that other Hindu deities, such as [[Brahma]] or [[Shiva]], might be equally the highest among the deities. Madhvacharya says that in the beginning there was only one God and that was [[Narayana]] or [[Vishnu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Famous Indian sages: their immortal messages|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dKnXAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Sagar Publications|page=356|year=1982|author=Vivek Ranjan Bhattacharya}}</ref> Madhvacharya states that the ultimate divine reality, which Hindu traditions refer to as [[Brahman]], and the individual souls, known as [[jiva|jīvātman]]s, exist as independent realities, and that these are distinct. Madhvacharya asserted, ''yathecchasi tatha kuru'', which Sharma translates and explains as "one has the right to choose between right and wrong, a choice each individual makes out of his own responsibility and his own risk".{{Sfn|Sharma|1962|p=361}}
Madhvism rejects not only the [[Advaita Vedanta]], or monism, of [[Shankaracharya]], but also the [[Vishistadvaita]], or qualified monism, of [[Ramanujacharya]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Indian Encyclopaedia: La Behmen-Maheya|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=4LqRXZPJTUoC|publisher=Genesis Publishing|author=Subodh Kapoor|year=2002|page=4425}}</ref> Madhva rejects Shankara's conception of the ''Nirguna Brahman''--that is, Brahman without characterisations--and accepts the conception of the ''Saguna Brahman''--that is, Brahman with characterisations--as the ultimate divine reality. In Madhva philosophy, Brahman possess all positive qualities; at the root of these are existence, consciousness, and bliss. An impersonal Brahman, such as Shankara's Nirguna Brahman cannot perform these functions. For Madhva, the personal Brahman is not different from Vishnu, whom Vaishavas consider to be the creator, the maintainer and destroyer of the world. According to the Madhva viewpoint, nothing can condition Brahman. According to Madhva, Brahman is neither the limited infinite divine reality of the [[Nyaya]] school nor a being in inseparable relation with matter and selves as in the philosophy of [[Ramanuja]]. Rather, Brahman is viewed as completely independent, but whilst the jivas are viewed as dependent upon Brahman for activity, knowledge, and existence. According to the Vaishnava viewpoint, Vishnu creates the world by his will and brings into existence the world of objects and selves. Objects and selves, the though real and irreducible to each other, are dependent on Brahman. At the time of dissolution of the world, material and objects are considered to be transformed into undifferentiated matter and selves into disembodied intelligence by Brahman; it is believed, even in the state of dissolution, that Brahman, matter, and the jivas remain distinct from one another, and do not merge with one another.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Oriental Philosophy and Religion: Hinduism : J-R|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=0TBTVPax4E8C|publisher=Global Vision Publishing House|author1=Nagendra Kr Singh|author2=A. P. Mishra|year=2005|page=473|isbn=9788182200739}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Metaphysics of Becoming: On the Relationship between Creativity and God in Whitehead and Supermind and Sachchidananda in Aurobindo|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=r97mBQAAQBAJ|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|author=Thomas Padiyath|page=157|accessdate=31 January 2014|isbn=9783110342772}}</ref>
==Bhakti movement==
===Haridasa movement=== {{Main article|Haridasa}}
The devotional movement of the [[Haridasa]] of [[Karnataka]] was an expression of [[Madhva]]'s religious thought. The Haridasa movement initiated by Madhva has had a deep impact on the people in different parts of the country.<ref>{{cite book|title=President R. Venkataraman selected speeches, Volume 1|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=BAy2AAAAIAAJ|author=Ramaswami Venkataraman|publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Govt. of India|year=1991|page=474|quote=}}</ref> The Haridasas were mostly [[Madhwas]] and almost exclusively of the Brahmin community.<ref>{{cite book|title=South Asian Intellectuals and Social Change: A Study of the Role of Vernacular-speaking Intelligentsia|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=5ZvZAAAAMAAJ|author=Yogendra K. Malik|publisher=Heritage|year=1981|page=262}}</ref>
==Institutions== Madhvacharya established many Mathas by defeating various acharya's of different sampradaya's.
===Monasteries=== Out of these 24 Mathas, the first eight are part of the [[Ashta Mathas of Udupi|Ashta (eight) mathas of Udupi]] who take turns once every two years ([[Paryaya]]) to worship Lord Krishna in at Udupi.The mathas which Madhva built exist until today, and continue the teachings and influence of Madhva<ref>{{cite book|title=Living Traditions in Contemporary Contexts: The Madhva Matha of Udupi|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=-utNEpTZWUkC|publisher=Orient Blackswan|year=2002|author=Vasudeva Rao|page=30}}</ref>
The table below gives an overview of the Eight largest Dvaita Mathas founded by Madhva, and their details.Madhva established more mathas locally for Vedanta studies and its propagation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Krishna in History, Thought, and Culture: An Encyclopedia of the Hindu Lord of Many Names: An Encyclopedia of the Hindu Lord of Many Names|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=4fw2DAAAQBAJ|page=165|publisher=ABC-CLIO|author=Lavanya Vemsani Ph.D.|accessdate=13 June 2016|isbn=9781610692113}}</ref> {{Main article|Ashta Mathas of Udupi}} {| class="wikitable" align=center style = " background: transparent; " |+ Ashta Mathas of Udupi |-style="text-align: center;" | width=60px style="background: #ffad66;" | Matha | width=120px style="background: #ffad66;"| First Swamiji |- | [[Pejawara Matha|Pejavara]]|||Adhokshaja Teertha |- | [[Palimaru]]|||Hrishikesha Teertha |- | [[Adamaru]]|||Narasimha Teertha |- | [[Puttige Matha|Puttige]]||| Upendra Teertha |- | [[Sodhe]]|||[[Vishnutirtha| Vishnu Teertha]] |- | [[Kaniyooru]]||| Rama Teertha |- | [[Shirur (Karnataka)|Shirur]]||| Vamana Teertha |- | [[Krishnapura Matha|Krishnapura]]||| Janardhana Teertha |- |}
The remaining Dvaita Vedanta mathas following Madhva Tradition include: {{div col}} * [[Uttaradi Matha]] * Raghavendra Matha * Vyasaraja Matha ** [[Vyasaraja Matha (Sosale)|Sosale Vyasaraja Matha]] ** Kundapura Vyasaraja Matha ** Sagarakatte Vyasaraja Matha
* Bhandarakeri Matha * Subramanya Matha * Chitrapura Matha * Bhimanakatte Matha * Madhva Kanva Matha * [[Kashi Math|Kashi Matha]] * [[Gokarna Matha|Partagali Jeevottama Matha]] *Arya Akshobhya Tirtha Matha ** Baligaru Arya Akshobhya Tirtha Matha ** Kudli Arya Akshobhya Tirtha Matha * Tambehalli Madhava Tirtha Matha * Mulbagalu Sripadaraja Matha {{div col end}}
Out of these [[Uttaradi Matha]], [[Vyasaraja Matha (Sosale)|Vyasaraja Matha]] and Raghavendra Matha enjoy the status of ''Matha-traya'' or the three premium madhva mathas descended from [[Jayatirtha]].{{Sfn|Sharma|2000|p=197}}
